00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:44.180
and found differences in the translation.

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:47.180
And you might wonder why that is.

00:03:47.180 --> 00:03:55.180
Oh, we'd never conclude that the translators had been unfaithful, or careless, or that they were running ahead of the organization.

00:03:55.180 --> 00:03:59.180
No, we trust our hardworking brothers and sisters.

00:03:59.180 --> 00:04:03.180
So we know there must be good reasons for the differences.

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:08.180
And the purpose of this brief discussion is to suggest what some of those reasons might be.

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:13.180
First, a word about one of the principles our translators follow.

00:04:13.180 --> 00:04:22.180
They're expected not only to render the thought in the English text accurately, but also to keep in mind the way people speak.

00:04:22.180 --> 00:04:31.180
So accuracy, clarity, and naturalness are needed while maintaining the dignity of our message.

00:04:31.180 --> 00:04:38.180
Now, what's involved in preparing a translation does both accurate and natural.

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:44.180
It's not as if the translators are like the Jewish scribes who made copies of the Hebrew Scriptures.

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:48.180
To make sure that the copies they made were accurate in every detail.

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:55.180
They would count not only every word, but also every letter they copied from the source text.

00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:57.180
Translations not like that.

00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:03.180
It's not as if there must be seven words in the target language if there are seven words in the English.

00:05:03.180 --> 00:05:10.180
Every word in the English may not be translated, but the complete thought of the English has to be there.

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:14.180
English makes effective use of repetition.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:16.180
What do we mean by that?

00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:26.180
Well, you can write one sentence in English, then repeat the same thought in slightly different words in the next sentence, and it sounds fine.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:34.180
But in some languages, to repeat a thought would be viewed as poor writing, and that wouldn't reflect well on our publications.

00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:45.180
So, in such cases, the translators are allowed to combine the two sentences into just one sentence as long as the thought is completely conveyed.

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:52.180
Or, they might make two sentences out of one long English sentence if that's more natural in the language.

00:05:52.180 --> 00:06:05.180
So, you can't always compare the length of an English paragraph with the length of the paragraph in the target language and say, hey, this paragraph is shorter than that paragraph.

00:06:05.180 --> 00:06:13.180
Sometimes we hear brothers who have learned a second language say, I don't see why the translators didn't follow the English word for word.

00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:17.180
After all, you can say that in the language.

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:27.180
Well, you may have the words, it may be possible to say that, but what a literal translation sounds strange to native speakers.

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:38.180
No matter how well a foreigner has learned a language, native speakers who speak the language well are usually the best judges of what is natural.

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:42.180
Modesty will help foreign speakers to recognize that.

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:47.459
There's another thing that foreign speakers need to be aware of.

00:06:47.459 --> 00:06:59.459
If they're vocal in their criticism of a certain translation, how would that affect the confidence of native speakers who have to rely on the translation for their spiritual food?

00:06:59.459 --> 00:07:07.459
Of course, nobody's perfect, and as long as translation is done by imperfect people, it won't be perfect.

00:07:07.459 --> 00:07:13.459
But rest assured that our translators take their work very seriously.

00:07:13.459 --> 00:07:18.459
